covered: Valid Request scenarios (successful 200 responses with default and with parameters)
Empty Response handling (no accounts, empty array)
Pagination basics (offset/limit usage, boundary and beyond data cases)
Authorization handling (401) including missing and invalid tokens
Error handling for invalid inputs (400 for invalid offset/limit/audit/booleans/integers)
Various edge cases (no query params, only one parameter, malformed inputs)
Large data volume and performance considerations (TC19, TC31)
Concurrency and integration scenarios (TC20, TC32, TC33)
Security considerations (SQL injection TC23, XSS TC24)
Partial and extra parameters handling (TC25, TC29, TC42, TC44, TC49/TC50 variants)
gaps: Caching behavior and headers (ETag, Cache-Control) not explicitly tested
Rate limiting / throttling scenarios not covered (multiple rapid requests) as per guidelines
403 Forbidden scenarios not clearly explicit (only 401 shown); need to confirm access control nuance
Explicit validation of response schemas across all parameter combinations (beyond “Account objects” vs schema integrity) could be more granular
Monitoring/observability aspects (logging/audit trace headers) not directly asserted in tests

Some very large-scale and extreme boundary tests (e.g., max offset and max limit combinations) could be more exhaustively covered (TC27–TC29 variants exist but may need concrete expectations for 200/400 in every edge)
recommendations: Add tests to validate caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) and ensure correct caching behavior for GET /1.0/kb/accounts/pagination
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests to verify system behavior under bursty traffic and ensure no rate-limit abuse
Clarify and test 403 Forbidden scenarios if there are authenticated users with insufficient privileges; ensure coverage beyond 401
Enhance schema validation checks across all parameter permutations to assert consistent response shape and field presence
Add observability checks (audit/log correlation headers) to ensure traceability across requests
Expand extreme-edge tests for offset/limit (e.g., max/min boundaries) with precise expected outcomes (empty array vs data) and document system constraints
